<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-07-17T19:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-07-17T19:36:00-05:00" n="319" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d319">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">714.1515/341: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">McMillin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Guatemala</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-07-17T18:00:00-06:36"><hi rend="italic">July 17,
                                            1920—6 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received July 18—6:30
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>116. Department’s 13, February 28th, 1 p.m., 57 July 2, 5 p.m. Upon
                                the recognition of this Government I presented Department’s 13
                                February 28th, 1 p.m. which was pending with the former
                                administration. I was promised an early answer.</p>
                            <p>Minister of Foreign Affairs informed me today that Guatemala and
                                Honduras are trying to agree on a compromise boundary with favorable
                                prospects. If successful they will send result to Washington to be
                                entered as final settlement.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">McMillin</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>